                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.20/327: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="to"
                            >Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-19T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 19, 1932—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>145. For the Minister. Your April 17, 11 a.m. The Department has no objection to
                    Trade Commissioner discussing “civilian aviation” with <persName
                        corresp="#p_STV1">Soong</persName>.</p>
                <p>However, in relation to plans of the Chinese Government in connection with
                    “military air training”, it is the Department’s opinion, known to and concurred
                    in by the War Department, that, in view of the present situation, it would be
                    inadvisable for this Government or any of its officers to be associated with
                    military training.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_CWR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
